<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8" />
  <title>CBRWS Schema Versions</title>
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1" />
</head>
<body>
<header>
  <h1>CBRWS Schema Versions</h1>
  <p>
    URL: <code>{{ cbrws_directory_url }}</code>
  </p>
</header>

<main>
  <section>
    <h2>Summary</h2>
    <p>{{ description }}</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Where This Page Fits</h2>
    <p>
      This page sits inside <code>/profiles</code> in the URL
      hierarchy of this web service. (In this documentation the word
      <em>endpoint</em> means a URL that responds to HTTP requests;
      the two terms are used interchangeably.)
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <code>/profiles</code> &mdash; the top-level index of every
        schema family published by this server. If you start there,
        this page is one of the entries listed.
      </li>
      <li>
        <code>/profiles/cbrws</code> &mdash; <strong>this page</strong>.
        It lists the versions of the CBRWS schema that the server
        currently publishes. A <em>schema family</em> is simply a
        named group of related schemas, usually one entry per
        version.
      </li>
      <li>
        <code>/profiles/cbrws/v1</code> &mdash; the v1 API
        specification for this web service. It is linked from the
        <a href="#directory-contents">Directory Contents</a> table
        below. Open it to see the shape of the responses returned by
        <code>/api</code> and the endpoints that <code>/api</code>
        links to.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      The path prefix <code>/profiles/</code> reflects a term from the
      HTTP standard RFC 6906, which calls this kind of specification a
      <em>profile</em>. In this documentation and in the rest of the
      codebase we use the word <em>schema</em> for the same idea; the
      URL path keeps the older name.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>What Is a "Schema"?</h2>
    <p>
      When a client calls an endpoint on this service (for example
      <code>/api</code>), the server returns a JSON document. A
      <em>schema</em> is a separate document that describes the
      shape of that JSON response: what fields it contains, what
      each field means, and what other URLs the response links to.
      You can think of a schema as the specification, or contract,
      for an endpoint's response.
    </p>
    <p>
      Every schema on this server is available in two formats from
      the same URL. The format you receive is selected by the
      <code>Accept</code> header the client sends with its request:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>HTML</strong> (<code>Accept: text/html</code>)
        &mdash; a human-readable documentation page that explains the
        response fields, the URLs the response links to, and the
        error conditions the endpoint can return. This is what a
        browser shows you, and it is the first place to look when you
        are learning the API.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>JSON Schema</strong>
        (<code>Accept: application/schema+json</code>) &mdash; a
        machine-readable JSON document that formally describes the
        response structure. A <em>JSON Schema</em> is itself a JSON
        document; it lists the expected fields and their types. A
        client can feed it to a JSON Schema validator library to
        check automatically that a response from the service has the
        expected shape.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Because an API's response format can change over time, schemas
      are versioned. This page lists the versions of the CBRWS
      schema that the server currently publishes.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="directory-contents">
    <h2>Directory Contents</h2>
    <p>The following CBRWS schema versions are available:</p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Version</th>
          <th>URL</th>
          <th>Description</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>v1</td>
          <td>
            <a href="{{ api_v1_schema_url }}"><code>{{ api_v1_schema_url }}</code></a>
          </td>
          <td>
            The v1 API specification. This page documents the
            response returned by <code>/api</code> (the service's
            top-level discovery endpoint) and the contract that its
            response follows. Open the URL in a browser to read the
            human-readable documentation, or request it with
            <code>Accept: application/schema+json</code> to fetch the
            machine-readable JSON Schema.
          </td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Content Negotiation</h2>
    <p>
      This directory page is itself available in two formats. Which
      one you receive depends on the <code>Accept</code> header in
      your request:
    </p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th><code>Accept</code> Header</th>
          <th>What You Get</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>
            <code>application/hal+json</code> (or omitted)
          </td>
          <td>
            A JSON document listing the schema versions as navigable
            links. This is the default and is intended for programs
            that walk the API automatically. (HAL is a convention for
            embedding navigation links inside JSON under a key named
            <code>_links</code>; the rest of the document is ordinary
            JSON.)
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>text/html</code> (or a browser)</td>
          <td>This human-readable page.</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p>Examples using curl:</p>
    <pre><code># Fetch the machine-readable HAL+JSON directory
curl -s -H "Accept: application/hal+json" {{ cbrws_directory_url }}

# Fetch the human-readable HTML page
curl -s -H "Accept: text/html" {{ cbrws_directory_url }}</code></pre>
  </section>
</main>

